</p>
<p>Ok, this object is actually a <code>PDOException</code>. Two Important things: <em>all</em> exceptions
are objects, and all exception classes ultimately extend PHP's base <code>Exception</code> class.
So if you could look at the source code for <code>PDOException</code>, you'd see that it
extends <code>Exception</code>:</p>
<p>And this ends up giving us a lot more flexibility when working with exceptions.
Why? Remember, we're pretending that - for some reason - we occasionally have some
database problems that cause a <code>PDOException</code> to be thrown. When that happens, we
want to recover and just show zero ships. And we've got that.</p>
<p>But what if something <em>else</em> goes wrong inside <code>fetchAllShipsData()</code> that has <em>nothing</em>
to do with talking to the database. Well, that would be truly unexpected, and in
those cases, I want to let the exception be thrown like normal so we can see it
while we're developing.</p>
<p>So here's the question: how can we catch <code>PDOException</code> objects, but not <em>any</em> others?
By changing the catch to <code>\PDOException</code>:</p>
